Overview
This Flask-based REST API allows users to import, store, and retrieve recipes from cooking websites. It uses web scraping to extract recipe data and stores it in a SQLite database for persistent access.

Core Features
1. Recipe Import
Endpoint: POST /recipes/import

When a user submits a recipe URL, the system:
Scrapes the website using recipe_scrapers
Extracts structured data (title, ingredients, instructions, etc.)
Parses instructions into individual steps
Identifies kitchen tools mentioned in the recipe
Stores everything in the database
Returns the complete recipe object

2. Recipe Storage
Database Schema:
id: Unique identifier for each recipe
user_id: Links recipes to specific users
url: Original source URL
title: Recipe name
ingredients_json: JSON array of ingredients
instructions: Raw instruction text
tools_json: JSON array of kitchen tools
image: Recipe image URL
total_time: Preparation + cooking time in minutes
yields: Serving size information
created_at: Timestamp of import

3. Recipe Retrieval
GET /users/<user_id>/recipes - List all recipes for a user (newest first)
GET /recipes/<recipe_id> - Get detailed information for a specific recipe

Key Functions Explained
scrape_recipe(url)
Takes a recipe URL
Uses recipe_scrapers to extract content

Returns a dictionary with:
title: Recipe name
ingredients: List of ingredients
instructions: Raw instruction text
steps: Instructions split into individual steps
tools: Kitchen tools identified
image: Recipe image URL
total_time: Total cooking time
yields: Serving size

-split_steps(instructions)
-Converts raw instruction text into a list of individual steps
-Filters out empty lines and trims whitespace
-Returns a clean, numbered list of instructions
-extract_tools(instructions, ingredients)
-Scans recipe text for common kitchen tools
-Searches both instructions and ingredients
-Returns a deduplicated list of tools (e.g., "oven", "skillet", "mixing bowl")

Data Flow
User submits URL → API validates input
Web scraping → Extract structured recipe data
Data processing → Split steps, identify tools
Database storage → Save as JSON + text fields
Response → Return complete recipe object

API Response Example 
{
  "id": 1,
  "user_id": "test-user",
  "url": "https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/recipes/easy-pancakes",
  "title": "Easy Pancakes",
  "ingredients": ["100g flour", "2 eggs", "300ml milk"],
  "instructions": "Mix ingredients... Cook until golden...",
  "steps": [
    "Mix ingredients in a bowl",
    "Heat a non-stick pan",
    "Cook until golden on both sides"
  ],
  "tools": ["bowl", "whisk", "frying pan", "spatula"],
  "image": "https://example.com/pancakes.jpg",
  "total_time": 20,
  "yields": "8 pancakes",
  "created_at": "2024-01-15T10:30:00"
}
Database Management
SQLite database (recipes.db) for simple deployment

Automatic table creation on startup

Schema migrations for new fields (like tools_json)

JSON storage for flexible data structures

Testing with PowerShell
# Import a recipe
$body = @{ url = "https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/recipes/easy-pancakes"; user_id = "test-user" } | ConvertTo-Json
Invoke-RestMethod -Method Post -Uri "http://127.0.0.1:5000/recipes/import" -ContentType "application/json" -Body $body

# List user recipes
Invoke-RestMethod -Method Get -Uri "http://127.0.0.1:5000/users/test-user/recipes"

# Get specific recipe
Invoke-RestMethod -Method Get -Uri "http://127.0.0.1:5000/recipes/1"